

üéì Git Day01 Practice Using IntelliJ IDEA (No Command Line)

üìå Goal:
Learn how to:
- Use Git inside IntelliJ
- Edit/Add .gitignore
- Commit changes with messages
- Push to GitHub
- Pull from GitHub
- View Git history (log)
- Understand Git changes visually

‚úÖ Step 1: Create a New Java Project

1. Open IntelliJ IDEA.
2. Click ‚ÄúFile > New > Project‚Äù.
3. Name your Java project: git-live-review

‚úÖ Step 1.1: Edit/Create a .gitignore File
----IGNORE IF FILE ALREADY EXISTS----
1. Right-click your project root ‚Üí New ‚Üí File
2. Name the file: `.gitignore`
---------------
3. Add the following contents:

# Ignore IntelliJ and build files
/.idea
/out
*.iml

This will prevent unnecessary files and folders from being tracked by Git,
such as IntelliJ config and compiled classes.

‚úÖ Step 2: Create a Java Package and Class

1. Create a new package "day01_commit_push_pull" under src.
2. Add new Java Class "Main"
4. Add the following code:

   public static void main(String[] args) {
       System.out.println("Hello, Git!");
   }

‚úÖ Step 3: Enable Git Integration in IntelliJ

1. Top menu: go to VCS ‚Üí Enable Version Control Integration.
2. Select Git from the list ‚Üí click OK.
3. IntelliJ initializes a local Git repository.
4. You‚Äôll now see files turn red in the Project pane (this means they are untracked).

‚úÖ Step 4.1: Initial Commit (Add all files to Git)

1. Go to Git ‚Üí Commit‚Ä¶
2. Select all files in the left panel.
3. Write commit message:
   ‚û§ Initial commit: added project structure and Main.java
4. Click Commit

‚úÖ Step 4.2: Add a new class and another commit
1. Create a new class Table
2. Add static method multiplicationTable(int num)
   ‚û§  prints multiplication table for the number
3. Call the method from Main class with different numbers
4. Make sure code runs properly then goto commit tab
5. Commit with message "Added Table class with multiplicationTable method"

‚úÖ Step 5.0: Login to GitHub in IntelliJ settings
1. Goto IntelliJ Settings -> Version Control -> GitHub -> Plus -> Login Via GitHub...

‚úÖ Step 5.1: Create a GitHub Repo

1. Log in to GitHub ‚Üí Click on Profile Round Icon on top right corner ‚Üí Your Repositories.
2. Click on New Repository button
3. Enter repository name: git-live-review
4. Choose visibility: Private
5. Click Create Repository.

‚úÖ Step 5.2: Copy GitHub repository URL and add to local remotes

1. Copy repository URL from GitHub
2. In IntelliJ ‚Üí Git menu ‚Üí Manage Remotes
3. Add new remote ‚Üí name: origin , URL: paste GitHub repo url ‚Üí OK

Now we successfully connected local git repository with remote GitHub repository
and ready for Push

‚úÖ Step 5.2: Push local commits to GitHub Repository

1. In IntelliJ ‚Üí Git menu ‚Üí Push...
2. Observe the commits then click on Push
3. Verify By going to GitHub and refresh the page
4. Click on Commits to see history
5. Click on Project name to go back to main Repository page

‚úÖ Step 6: Make Your First Code Change and Commit

1. Open Main.java and change the message:
   System.out.println("First change: practicing Git commit!");
2. IntelliJ shows a blue bar next to the modified line.
3. Go to Git ‚Üí Commit‚Ä¶
   ‚û§ Message: Updated print message for Git practice
4. Click Commit and Push.

‚úÖ Step 7: Add a New Class and Commit It

1. Right-click day01 package ‚Üí New ‚Üí Java Class.
2. Name it Helper.
3. Add the following:
   public class Helper {
       public static String getGreeting() {
           return "Hello from Helper!";
       }
   }
4. Now update Main.java by adding the line:
   System.out.println(Helper.getGreeting());

5. Go to Git ‚Üí Commit‚Ä¶
   ‚û§ Message: Added Helper class with getGreeting method and used it in Main
6. Click Commit and Push.

‚úÖ Step 8: View Git History (Log)

1. Go to Git ‚Üí Show Git Log.
2. A bottom panel opens showing all commits:
   - Each commit has a message, author, date/time.
   - You can click each commit to view changes.

‚úÖ Step 9: Pull Changes from GitHub

1. Open your GitHub repo in the browser.
2. Click Main.java ‚Üí Edit (pencil icon).
3. Add this line inside main():
   System.out.println("This change was made from GitHub!");
4. Scroll down ‚Üí Commit changes.

5. Back in IntelliJ:
   - Go to Git ‚Üí Pull.
   - IntelliJ will fetch and merge the change from GitHub.

‚úÖ Confirm the line appears in your IntelliJ file.

‚úÖ Step 10: Add One More Commit Locally

1. Add a new method in Helper.java:
   public static int getRandomNumber() {
       return (int)(Math.random() * 100);
   }

2. Use it in Main.java:
   System.out.println("Random number: " + Helper.getRandomNumber());

3. Commit and push:
   - Message: Added getRandomNumber method in Helper

üîÅ Extra Practice Ideas for you

- Delete a line and commit the deletion.
- Rename a method and see what IntelliJ tracks.
- Add a .txt file and commit it.

üß† Git Concepts Recap (GUI Terms)

| Concept           | Meaning                                  | IntelliJ Action             |
|------------------|------------------------------------------|-----------------------------|
| Commit           | Save changes locally with message         | Git ‚Üí Commit‚Ä¶               |
| Push             | Send local commits to GitHub              | Git ‚Üí Push                  |
| Pull             | Fetch latest from GitHub                  | Git ‚Üí Pull                  |
| Log              | View history of all commits               | Git ‚Üí Log                   |
